{"id":2348,"date":"2020-12-11T10:00:36","date_gmt":"2020-12-10T23:00:36","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/?p=2348"},"modified":"2020-12-11T10:51:24","modified_gmt":"2020-12-10T23:51:24","slug":"particle-ni","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-ni\/","title":{"rendered":"How to use the particle NI for destinations, locations and time"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>The particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is extremely common, and a big reason for that is because it has so many applications.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In this article we\u2019re going to look at the three most important uses of the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>To mark the <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-ni\/#destination\">destination<\/a><\/strong> of an action involving movement<\/li><li>To mark the <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-ni\/#location-of-existence\">location where something exists<\/a><\/strong><\/li><li>To mark the <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-ni\/#timing\">time when an action takes place<\/a><\/strong><\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>For each of these we will look at how and when to use the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> in a sentence, common situations when <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is used, as well as some situations where <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> isn\u2019t the right particle to choose.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There are other relatively less-common uses of the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> that we won&#8217;t cover here. However, those can mostly be thought of as adaptations of the above anyway.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>You may notice, too, that the above three all relate to defining things in the dimensions of time and space, so there is a connection between them.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In practice, however, it pays to look at each major use individually, so let\u2019s do that!<\/p>\n\n\n\n<!--more-->\n\n\n\n<div class=\"rw-toc\">\n<div class=\"rw-toc-title\">Table of Contents<\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#destination\"><strong>Use #1: To mark the destination of an action involving movement<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div class=\"rw-sub-contents\">\n<div><a href=\"#dest-ni-usage\">How to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to define a destination<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#dest-notes\">Notes about the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> as a destination marker<\/a><\/div>\n<div class=\"rw-sub-contents\">\n<div><a href=\"#unexpected\">Situations where you might not expect <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to be used<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#ni-vs-he\"><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;He&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3078\u300d<\/span> &#8211; A similar but subtly different particle<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#passive-verbs\">The meaning flips with passive verbs<\/a><\/div>\n<\/div><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#location-of-existence\"><strong>Use #2: To mark the location where something exists<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div class=\"rw-sub-contents\"><div><a href=\"#loc-ni-usage\">How to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to define a location where something exists<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#there-is\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> when saying, \u201cthere is\u2026\u201d, in Japanese<\/a><\/div><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#timing\"><strong>Use #3: To mark the time when an action takes place<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div class=\"rw-sub-contents\"><div><a href=\"#timing-ni-usage\">How to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to define time when an action takes place<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#time-not-ni\">Time expressions that don\u2019t use the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#key-takeaways\"><strong>Key Takeaways<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"destination\"><strong>Use #1: To mark the destination of an action involving movement<\/strong><\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Some verbs describe actions that involve the movement of someone or something from one place to another, such as \u201cgo\u201d, \u201ccome\u201d, \u201csend\u201d or \u201cgive\u201d. The destination of such actions can be marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"dest-ni-usage\"><strong>How to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to define a destination<\/strong><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>To define the destination of an action involving movement, we can place the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> after the word or phrase that describes the destination.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This &#8220;destination + <span class=\"ilRom\">ni<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u306b<\/span>&#8221; combination then fits into our <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-sentence-structure\/\">model for Japanese sentence structure<\/a> like so:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large ilRom\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"493\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-romaji-1024x493.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2593\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-romaji-1024x493.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-romaji-300x145.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-romaji-768x370.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-romaji-1536x740.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-romaji.png 1600w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large ilKana\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"493\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-hiragana-1024x493.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2594\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-hiragana-1024x493.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-hiragana-300x145.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-hiragana-768x370.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-hiragana-1536x740.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-destination-ni-hiragana.png 1600w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Here it is in an example sentence:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/01-gakko-ikimashita-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Ry\u016bta wa gakk\u014d ni ikimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2536\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/01-gakko-ikimashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/01-gakko-ikimashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/01-gakko-ikimashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/01-gakko-ikimashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/01-gakko-ikimashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Ryuta went to school.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Ryuta went to school.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Ry\u016bta wa gakk\u014d ni ikimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f \u306f \u304c\u3063\u3053\u3046 \u306b \u3044\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u306f<ruby>\u5b66\u6821<rt>\u304c\u3063\u3053\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s break this down.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Firstly, the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wa&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306f\u300d<\/span> tells us that <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ry\u016bta&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u300d<\/span> is the topic of this sentence, which means that this sentence is talking about Ryuta.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The verb at the end of the sentence is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ikimashita&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201cwent\u201d. This is obviously an action that involves movement.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Lastly, the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;gakk\u014d&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5b66\u6821<rt>\u304c\u3063\u3053\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201cschool\u201d, is marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>. This tells us that school is the destination of the action described by the verb, which as we know is \u201cwent\u201d.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In other words, \u201cRyuta went to school\u201d.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s try another example. This time we\u2019ll add another element into the mix to see how that affects things:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/02-okaasan-tegami-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Ry\u016bta wa ok\u0101san ni tegami wo okurimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2537\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/02-okaasan-tegami-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/02-okaasan-tegami-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/02-okaasan-tegami-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/02-okaasan-tegami-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/02-okaasan-tegami-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Ryuta sent a letter to (his)* mother.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Ryuta sent a letter to (his)* mother.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Ry\u016bta wa ok\u0101san ni tegami wo okurimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f \u306f \u304a\u304b\u3042\u3055\u3093 \u306b \u3066\u304c\u307f \u3092 \u304a\u304f\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u306f\u304a<ruby>\u6bcd<rt>\u304b\u3042<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3055\u3093\u306b<ruby>\u624b\u7d19<rt>\u3066\u304c\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u9001<rt>\u304a\u304f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-sidebar\">*There\u2019s no need to include a Japanese equivalent to the word \u201chis\u201d here \u2013 it is implied from context that it is his own mother. If we were talking about someone else\u2019s mother, that would have to be specified.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Like before, the sentence is talking about <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ry\u016bta&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u300d<\/span>, who is the topic marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wa&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306f\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This time, the verb is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;okurimashita&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u9001<rt>\u304a\u304f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201csent\u201d. We therefore know that this sentence is saying that Ryuta sent something.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In this sentence, we have two pieces of information in the \u2018Other information\u2019 section. Here\u2019s what they tell us:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">ok\u0101san ni<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u304a\u304b\u3042\u3055\u3093 \u306b<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u304a<ruby>\u6bcd<rt>\u304b\u3042<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3055\u3093\u306b<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ok\u0101san&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304a<ruby>\u6bcd<rt>\u304b\u3042<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3055\u3093\u300d<\/span>, which means \u201cmother\u201d, is marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>, so this means that Ryuta\u2019s mother is the destination of the action.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"romaji\">tegami wo<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3066\u304c\u307f \u3092<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u624b\u7d19<rt>\u3066\u304c\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>As you probably know, <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-wo\/\">the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> marks the object of the verb<\/a> \u2013 that is, the thing the action is done to.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In this case, that \u201cthing\u201d is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;tegami&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u624b\u7d19<rt>\u3066\u304c\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201cletter\u201d, so the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> in this sentence tells us that it was a letter that was sent.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Putting this all together we get:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Ryuta sent a letter to his mother.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">ry\u016bta wa ok\u0101san ni tegami wo okurimashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f \u306f \u304a\u304b\u3042\u3055\u3093 \u306b \u3066\u304c\u307f \u3092 \u304a\u304f\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u306f\u304a<ruby>\u6bcd<rt>\u304b\u3042<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3055\u3093\u306b<ruby>\u624b\u7d19<rt>\u3066\u304c\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u9001<rt>\u304a\u304f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-group rw-sidebar\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow\">\n<p>An important point here is that, because we have particles marking each piece of the sentence, we can actually change the word order without changing the meaning. Let\u2019s try it:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/03-tegami-okaasan-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Ry\u016bta wa ok\u0101san ni tegami wo okurimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2538\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/03-tegami-okaasan-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/03-tegami-okaasan-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/03-tegami-okaasan-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/03-tegami-okaasan-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/03-tegami-okaasan-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Ryuta sent a letter to his mother.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Ryuta sent a letter to his mother.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">ry\u016bta wa tegami wo ok\u0101san ni okurimashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f \u306f \u3066\u304c\u307f \u3092 \u304a\u304b\u3042\u3055\u3093 \u306b \u304a\u304f\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u306f<ruby>\u624b\u7d19<rt>\u3066\u304c\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u304a<ruby>\u6bcd<rt>\u304b\u3042<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3055\u3093\u306b<ruby>\u9001<rt>\u304a\u304f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>We have swapped the order of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ok\u0101san ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304a<ruby>\u6bcd<rt>\u304b\u3042<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3055\u3093\u306b\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;tegami wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u624b\u7d19<rt>\u3066\u304c\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u300d<\/span>, but because we kept the particles with their respective words, their roles haven\u2019t changed. That is:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;tegami&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u624b\u7d19<rt>\u3066\u304c\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> is marked by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>, so it is still the object \u2013 ie. the thing that was sent.<\/li><li><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ok\u0101san&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304a<ruby>\u6bcd<rt>\u304b\u3042<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3055\u3093\u300d<\/span> is marked by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>, so it is still the destination to which the letter was sent.<\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>There is a slight difference in emphasis between the two word orderings, but the action being described is the same. Generally, the former is more natural. You can <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-word-order\/\">read more about natural word order in Japanese sentences here<\/a>.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>From our two examples, you may also notice that there are two kinds of actions that can have a destination:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\" type=\"1\"><li>Words like \u201cgo\u201d and \u201ccome\u201d where the person performing the action is also the person who moves.<\/li><li>Words like \u201csend\u201d and \u201cgive\u201d, where the person performing the action is separate from the person or thing that moves (eg. if I send an email, I do the sending, but it is the email that does the moving)<\/li><\/ol>\n\n\n\n<p>The use of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is the same in both cases, as it just marks the destination to which the person or thing moves.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"dest-notes\"><strong>Notes about the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> as a destination marker<\/strong><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>For this use of &#8220;ni&#8221; in particular, there are a few tricky little things that can potentially be quite confusing. To try to pre-empt that, let&#8217;s take a look at the most important ones.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"unexpected\">Situations where you might not expect <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to be used<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>This use of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is most commonly translated to English as the preposition \u201cto\u201d &#8211; that&#8217;s typically how we identify destinations in English. However, there are a few verbs that use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to mark a destination where we certainly wouldn&#8217;t use &#8220;to&#8221; in English, and this makes them quite unintuitive to English speakers.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Two examples of this are <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;suwarimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5ea7<rt>\u3059\u308f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201csit\u201d, and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;norimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u4e57<rt>\u306e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> meaning \u201cride\u201d. Basically, for these verbs and a few others like them, the thing that is sat on, ridden, etc., can be thought of as the destination of these actions.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>For example, if I ride a bicycle, the bicycle can be thought of as the destination of my act of riding. Here it is in a sentence:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/04-jitensha-norimashita-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Ry\u016bta wa jitensha ni norimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2539\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/04-jitensha-norimashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/04-jitensha-norimashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/04-jitensha-norimashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/04-jitensha-norimashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/04-jitensha-norimashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Ryuta rode a bicycle.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Ryuta rode a bicycle.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Ry\u016bta wa jitensha ni norimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f \u306f \u3058\u3066\u3093\u3057\u3083 \u306b \u306e\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u306f<ruby>\u81ea\u8ee2\u8eca<rt>\u3058\u3066\u3093\u3057\u3083<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u4e57<rt>\u306e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>It may help to think of the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;norimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u4e57<rt>\u306e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> (to ride) as describing the act of <em>getting on<\/em> something, as opposed to <em>being on<\/em> something, as is implied in English.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"ni-vs-he\"><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;He&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3078\u300d<\/span> &#8211; A similar but subtly different particle<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>Another particle, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;he&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3078\u300d<\/span>, has a very similar purpose to this use of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>, but it is subtly different.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The main difference is that <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;he&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3078\u300d<\/span> marks the <strong><u>direction<\/u><\/strong> of movement, while <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> marks a <strong><u>destination<\/u><\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>These can be the same thing, but there are situations where they certainly are not the same, so they are not always interchangeable.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>For example, if you were talking about somebody going to the north, you might say:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/05-kita-ikimashita-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Ry\u016bta wa kita he ikimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2540\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/05-kita-ikimashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/05-kita-ikimashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/05-kita-ikimashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/05-kita-ikimashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/05-kita-ikimashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Ryuta went north.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Ryuta went north.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Ry\u016bta wa kita he ikimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f \u306f \u304d\u305f \u3078 \u3044\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u306f<ruby>\u5317<rt>\u304d\u305f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3078<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>You generally would not, however, use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> here, since \u201cnorth\u201d is not a place that could be considered a destination. It is only a direction, so only <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;he&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3078\u300d<\/span> should be used in this situation.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The opposite situation is less common, at least with concrete actions like \u201cgoing\u201d and \u201csending\u201d. For example, \u201cTokyo\u201d is a place, and can be both a destination and a direction. That is, you can go to Tokyo, or you can go in the direction of Tokyo. You could therefore use either <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> or <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;he&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3078\u300d<\/span> in the following sentence:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"335\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/06-tokyo-he_ni-ikimashita-1024x335.png\" alt=\"Ry\u016bta wa Tokyo [ ni \/ he ] ikimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2541\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/06-tokyo-he_ni-ikimashita-1024x335.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/06-tokyo-he_ni-ikimashita-300x98.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/06-tokyo-he_ni-ikimashita-768x251.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/06-tokyo-he_ni-ikimashita-1536x503.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/06-tokyo-he_ni-ikimashita-2048x670.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Ryuta went to Tokyo.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Ryuta went to Tokyo.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Ry\u016bta wa Tokyo [ ni \/ he ] ikimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f \u306f \u3068\u3046\u304d\u3087\u3046 [ \u306b\u30fb\u3078 ] \u3044\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u308a\u3085\u3046\u305f\u306f<ruby>\u6771\u4eac<rt>\u3068\u3046\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby> [ \u306b\u30fb\u3078 ] <ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>There is a difference between these two, but it is so subtle that most Japanese people probably wouldn\u2019t be able to explain it to you.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s not really worth worrying about, but when in doubt, I recommend the use of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> as it tends to be more widely used, particularly with more abstract expressions.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"passive-verbs\">The meaning flips with passive verbs<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>When using verbs that are passive in nature, the role defined by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> flips from the destination to the origin.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>That sounds like it could get confusing, but until you learn the more advanced topic of passive verbs, there is only really one verb where you need to worry about this.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>That verb is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, which means \u201creceive\u201d, and <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/giving-and-receiving\/\">my detailed article about giving and receiving in Japanese<\/a> explains everything you need to know, including the appropriate use of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The vast majority of verbs where <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> flips to mark the origin is with regular verbs in their passive form. For example, while <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;\u012bmasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u8a00<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> means \u201csay\u201d, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;iwaremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u8a00<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> means \u201cis told\u201d.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>As I said, this is a more advanced topic, and there are other particle gymnastics involved with passive verbs, so we won\u2019t get into it here. If you\u2019re interested, <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/\">my book<\/a> covers them in Chapter 12.4.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-group rw-sidebar\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow\">\n<p>Before we go any further, I want to strongly suggest something\u2026.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong><em>Avoid translating particles into English prepositions, or vice versa.<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There are situations where <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> could be translated into English as \u201cin\u201d, \u201con\u201d, \u201cat\u201d or \u201cto\u201d. There are other possible translations as well.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The important point to remember is that the reasons we choose, for example, \u201cin\u201d in one case and \u201cat\u201d in another, is completely different to the reasons we choose <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> over another particle.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Sometimes certain particles translate fairly consistently into a particular preposition, but much of the time it is not that simple.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Rather than translating, focus on understanding the underlying purpose of each particle (and each of its uses). That is the key to mastering them.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"location-of-existence\"><strong>Use #2: To mark the location where something exists<\/strong><\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Most actions take place in a location, but there are a few verbs that describe the act of simply \u201cbeing\u201d in a location. For these, the location is marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"loc-ni-usage\"><strong>How to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to define a location where something exists<\/strong><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>When we want to describe where something is &#8220;being&#8221; or &#8220;existing&#8221;, we place the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> immediately after the word or phrase that describes the location of existence.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Just as we saw when using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to mark the destination, this &#8220;location + <span class=\"ilRom\">ni<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u306b<\/span>&#8221; combination belongs in the &#8216;Other Information&#8217; section of our sentence diagram:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large ilRom\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"493\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-romaji-1024x493.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2595\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-romaji-1024x493.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-romaji-300x145.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-romaji-768x370.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-romaji-1536x740.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-romaji.png 1600w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large ilKana\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"493\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-hiragana-1024x493.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2597\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-hiragana-1024x493.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-hiragana-300x145.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-hiragana-768x370.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-hiragana-1536x740.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-location-ni-hiragana.png 1600w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The important point with this use of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is that it should only be used with verbs that describe something equivalent to &#8220;being&#8221; or &#8220;existing&#8221;. In practice, there are two main verbs that this applies to &#8211; <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;arimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;Imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;arimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> both mean \u201cto be\u201d or \u201cis\u201d. The difference is that <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is used to describe the \u201cbeing\u201d of living things, while <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;arimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is used for non-living things.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s see an example:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/07-toshokan-imashita-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Mana wa toshokan ni imashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2542\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/07-toshokan-imashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/07-toshokan-imashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/07-toshokan-imashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/07-toshokan-imashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/07-toshokan-imashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Mana was at the library.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Mana was at the library.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Mana wa toshokan ni imashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u307e\u306a \u306f \u3068\u3057\u3087\u304b\u3093 \u306b \u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u307e\u306a\u306f<ruby>\u56f3\u66f8\u9928<rt>\u3068\u3057\u3087\u304b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b\u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>This should be fairly self-explanatory:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>Mana is the topic, marked by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wa&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306f\u300d<\/span><\/li><li>The verb is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imashita&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u300d<\/span>, which means \u201cwas\u201d (the past tense of \u201cis\u201d)<\/li><li>The location where Mana \u201cis\u201d is the library<\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>Now, it&#8217;s important to remember that <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> should only be used like this to mark a location for a verb describing existence or \u201cbeing\u201d.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here\u2019s a similar example where <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> should NOT be used:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/08-toshokan-hon-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Mana wa toshokan de hon wo yomimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2543\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/08-toshokan-hon-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/08-toshokan-hon-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/08-toshokan-hon-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/08-toshokan-hon-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/08-toshokan-hon-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Mana read a book at the library.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Mana read a book at the library.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Mana wa toshokan de hon wo yomimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u307e\u306a \u306f \u3068\u3057\u3087\u304b\u3093 \u3067 \u307b\u3093 \u3092 \u3088\u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u307e\u306a\u306f<ruby>\u56f3\u66f8\u9928<rt>\u3068\u3057\u3087\u304b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3067<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u8aad<rt>\u3088<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Unlike our example that used <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, this sentence describes an action that is <em>taking place<\/em> at the library. This is different from <em>being<\/em> at the library.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The location where an action takes place is marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;de&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u300d<\/span>, not <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>You can learn more about this in my article, <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/ni-vs-de\/\">Ni vs De: How to choose between these two location-defining particles<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s try an example using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;arimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/09-hon-tsukue-1024x198.png\" alt=\"hon wa tsukue ni arimasu.\" class=\"wp-image-2544\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/09-hon-tsukue-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/09-hon-tsukue-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/09-hon-tsukue-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/09-hon-tsukue-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/09-hon-tsukue-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>The book is on the desk.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">The book is on the desk.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">hon wa tsukue ni arimasu.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u307b\u3093 \u306f \u3064\u304f\u3048 \u306b \u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u673a<rt>\u3064\u304f\u3048<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Notice that this follows the exact same pattern as the <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> example.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The two verbs have the same meaning and are used in the same way as each other. The only difference is that <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is for living things, and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;arimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is for everything else.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"there-is\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> when saying, &#8220;there is&#8230;&#8221;, in Japanese<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>The other major phrasing that combines <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> with the verbs <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;arimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is the Japanese equivalent of the expression, &#8220;there is&#8230;&#8221;.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here\u2019s a modified version of our last example that applies this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/10-tsukue-hon-1024x198.png\" alt=\"tsukue ni hon ga arimasu.\" class=\"wp-image-2545\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/10-tsukue-hon-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/10-tsukue-hon-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/10-tsukue-hon-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/10-tsukue-hon-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/10-tsukue-hon-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>There is a book on the desk.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">There is a book on the desk.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">tsukue ni hon ga arimasu.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u3064\u304f\u3048 \u306b \u307b\u3093 \u304c \u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u673a<rt>\u3064\u304f\u3048<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>You&#8217;ll notice that the unique pieces of information in this sentence are the same as our previous example. We have:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>A book<\/li><li>A desk<\/li><li>A verb describing \u201cbeing\u201d<\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>In other words, both sentences describe the existence of a thing (the book) in a particular location (the desk).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The difference, of course, is the phrasing. By not including a topic and instead marking <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;hon&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> with <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-ga\/\">the subject particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ga&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304c\u300d<\/span><\/a>, we have changed the meaning of the sentence from, &#8220;The book is on the table&#8221;, to something closer to, &#8220;There is a book on the table&#8221;.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We won\u2019t go into this too much, but just as is the case in the English translations, the first example emphasizes <strong><em>where<\/em><\/strong> the book is, while the \u201cThere is\u2026\u201d example emphasizes the <strong><em>thing<\/em><\/strong> that is on the desk.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To understand why, it might help to think of it this way:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>the first sentence is <em>about <\/em>a book (ie. the book is the topic), and describes what that book is doing<\/li><li>the second sentence is not really &#8220;about&#8221; anything, and is simply a description of something being somewhere<\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>The following two articles should help to explain this further.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Read also:<\/strong> <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-ga\/\">The Japanese particle &#8220;ga&#8221;: What it&#8217;s for and when to use it (and not &#8220;wa&#8221;)<\/a><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Read also:<\/strong> <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wa-vs-ga\/\">The difference between the particles &#8220;wa&#8221; and &#8220;ga&#8221;<\/a><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ultimately, the main thing we are concerned about here is that in both cases, the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> marks the location where the thing is <em>being<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>And for the sake of clarity, the \u201cThere is\u2026\u201d equivalent phrasing works with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> too, such as in this example:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/11-toshokan-tori-1024x198.png\" alt=\"toshokan ni tori ga imasu.\" class=\"wp-image-2546\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/11-toshokan-tori-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/11-toshokan-tori-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/11-toshokan-tori-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/11-toshokan-tori-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/11-toshokan-tori-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>There is a bird in the library.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">There is a bird in the library.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">toshokan ni tori ga imasu.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u3068\u3057\u3087\u304b\u3093 \u306b \u3068\u308a \u304c \u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u56f3\u66f8\u9928<rt>\u3068\u3057\u3087\u304b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u9ce5<rt>\u3068\u308a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"timing\"><strong>Use #3: To mark the time when an action takes place<\/strong><\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>There are a three main types of time expressions:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>Timing &#8211; when an action takes place<\/li><li>Frequency &#8211; how often an action occurs<\/li><li>Duration &#8211; how long an action goes on for<\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>Expressions describing the last two &#8211; frequency and duration &#8211; act more like <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-adverbs\/\">adverbs<\/a> and usually don&#8217;t need a particle.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The first one, however, is where we sometimes need the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"timing-ni-usage\"><strong>How to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to define time when an action takes place<\/strong><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>To define the timing of an action, we can place the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> after the word or phrase that describes the time it happened.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This \u201ctime phrase + <span class=\"ilRom\">ni<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u306b<\/span>\u201d combination can then go in one of two locations:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\" type=\"1\"><li>At the beginning of the sentence, before the topic<\/li><li>Somewhere between the topic (marked by particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wa&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306f\u300d<\/span>) and the verb<\/li><\/ol>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s see this in our diagram:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large ilRom\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"493\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-romaji-1024x493.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2596\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-romaji-1024x493.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-romaji-300x145.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-romaji-768x370.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-romaji-1536x740.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-romaji.png 1600w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large ilKana\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"493\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-hiragana-1024x493.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2598\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-hiragana-1024x493.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-hiragana-300x145.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-hiragana-768x370.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-hiragana-1536x740.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/12\/00-timing-ni-hiragana.png 1600w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>What this essentially means is that timing phrases can appear anywhere in the sentence before the verb. Easy!<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here\u2019s an example using option 1.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/12-kayobi-masaki-eiga-1024x198.png\" alt=\"kay\u014dbi ni Masaki wa eiga wo mimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2547\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/12-kayobi-masaki-eiga-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/12-kayobi-masaki-eiga-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/12-kayobi-masaki-eiga-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/12-kayobi-masaki-eiga-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/12-kayobi-masaki-eiga-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>On Tuesday, Masaki watched a movie.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">On Tuesday, Masaki watched a movie.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">kay\u014dbi ni Masaki wa eiga wo mimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073 \u306b \u307e\u3055\u304d \u306f \u3048\u3044\u304c \u3092 \u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b\u307e\u3055\u304d\u306f<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Now here\u2019s the same sentence using option 2.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/13-masaki-kayobi-eiga-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Masaki wa kay\u014dbi ni eiga wo mimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2548\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/13-masaki-kayobi-eiga-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/13-masaki-kayobi-eiga-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/13-masaki-kayobi-eiga-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/13-masaki-kayobi-eiga-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/13-masaki-kayobi-eiga-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>On Tuesday, Masaki watched a movie.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">On Tuesday, Masaki watched a movie.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Masaki wa kay\u014dbi ni eiga wo mimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u307e\u3055\u304d \u306f \u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073 \u306b \u3048\u3044\u304c \u3092 \u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u307e\u3055\u304d\u306f<ruby>\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Both sentences mean the same thing. What\u2019s more, since elements in the \u2018Other information\u2019 section can be included in any order, we can also put <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kay\u014dbi ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b\u300d<\/span> <em>after<\/em> <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;eiga wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u300d<\/span>, like this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/14-masaki-eiga-kayobi-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Masaki wa eiga wo kay\u014dbi ni mimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2549\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/14-masaki-eiga-kayobi-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/14-masaki-eiga-kayobi-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/14-masaki-eiga-kayobi-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/14-masaki-eiga-kayobi-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/14-masaki-eiga-kayobi-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Masaki watched a movie on Tuesday.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Masaki watched a movie on Tuesday.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Masaki wa eiga wo kay\u014dbi ni mimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u307e\u3055\u304d \u306f \u3048\u3044\u304c \u3092 \u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073 \u306b \u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u307e\u3055\u304d\u306f<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>So, is there a difference? Yes and no.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The fundamental meaning of all three sentences is the same; that is, they all tell us that Masaki saw a movie on Tuesday.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>However, the emphasis of each sentence is different. Generally, words that appear closer to the end of a sentence are more important.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>So, the first two versions, where the <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kay\u014dbi ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b\u300d<\/span> is near the beginning, emphasize more <strong><em>what Masaki did<\/em><\/strong> on Tuesday.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The last example, however, has <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kay\u014dbi ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b\u300d<\/span> as the last element before the verb. This is less common, but would be appropriate when you want to emphasis <strong><em>when<\/em><\/strong> Masaki did what he did.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The different English translations provided for the above examples (with &#8220;on Tuesday&#8221; appearing either at the beginning of end of the sentence) highlight this somewhat, although none should be considered &#8220;perfect&#8221; translations; there is no such thing.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Read also:<\/strong> <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-word-order\/\">A Visual Guide to Japanese Word Order<\/a><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"time-not-ni\"><strong>Time expressions that don\u2019t use the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span><\/strong><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Now, there\u2019s one more fairly important thing to note here\u2026<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In the diagram, you may have noticed that the line surrounding the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> for Timing is dotted, unlike the rest of the particles.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is because we don\u2019t always need the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> with time expressions. Depending on the type of time phrase being used, we either need to use the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>, or use no particle at all.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>My article, <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/time-expressions\/\">Japanese Expressions of Time (and when to use the particle &#8220;ni&#8221;)<\/a>, discusses this in much more detail, but to summarize, the two groups of timing expressions are as follows:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\" type=\"1\"><li>Phrases that describe a point in time relative to \u201cnow\u201d<\/li><li>Time phrases that rely on context for specificity<\/li><\/ol>\n\n\n\n<p>To simplify things, these groups almost perfectly match up with English expressions of time.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here&#8217;s a basic summary:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/time-expressions\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"513\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Using-particle-ni-with-Japanese-time-expressions-1024x513.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2067\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Using-particle-ni-with-Japanese-time-expressions-1024x513.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Using-particle-ni-with-Japanese-time-expressions-300x150.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Using-particle-ni-with-Japanese-time-expressions-768x385.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Using-particle-ni-with-Japanese-time-expressions-1536x769.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/Using-particle-ni-with-Japanese-time-expressions.png 1825w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/a><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Group 1<\/strong> includes phrases where <strong>the point in time being referred to changes as time progresses<\/strong>.<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>This includes words like <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ima&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u4eca<rt>\u3044\u307e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (now), <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ky\u014d&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u4eca\u65e5<rt>\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (today), <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ashita&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u660e\u65e5<rt>\u3042\u3057\u305f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (tomorrow) and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;sensh\u016b&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5148\u9031<rt>\u305b\u3093\u3057\u3085\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (last week). Notice that all of these words refer to points in time that change depending on when they are said.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In Japanese, <strong>these phrases do not need to be followed by a particle<\/strong> when used in a sentence. This is much like English, where these phrases can be used in a sentence without a preposition (such as \u201cin\u201d, \u201con\u201d, or \u201cat\u201d).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Group 2<\/strong> includes phrases that describe <strong>points in time that occur repeatedly<\/strong>.<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>They therefore rely on context for us to know exactly which point in time is being referred to.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This includes phrases like <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;goji&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>5\u6642<rt>\u3054\u3058<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (5 o\u2019clock), <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kay\u014dbi&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (Tuesday), <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;sangatsu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>3\u6708<rt>\u3055\u3093\u304c\u3064<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (March) or <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;natsu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u590f<rt>\u306a\u3064<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (summer). Notice that each of these words could refer to many different points in time. We therefore need context to tell us <strong><em>which<\/em><\/strong> Monday or <strong><em>which<\/em><\/strong> summer is being talked about.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In Japanese, <strong>these phrases should be followed by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span><\/strong> when used in a sentence (eg. <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kay\u014dbi ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\"><ruby>\u300c\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b\u300d<\/span>). Again, this is comparable to English, where these phrases usually need to be used with a preposition of time (eg. \u201cat 5 o\u2019clock\u201d, \u201con Tuesday\u201d, etc.)<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Both groups follow the same sentence position rules.<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>We saw already how a time phrase from Group 2 can be used in a sentence. Rest assured that the only difference when using Group 1 time expressions is that <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is not needed.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To highlight this, here are the two sentence structure options for a slightly modified version of our example from earlier:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/15-kino-masaki-eiga-1024x198.png\" alt=\"kin\u014d, Masaki wa eiga wo mimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2550\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/15-kino-masaki-eiga-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/15-kino-masaki-eiga-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/15-kino-masaki-eiga-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/15-kino-masaki-eiga-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/15-kino-masaki-eiga-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Yesterday, Masaki watched a movie.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Yesterday, Masaki watched a movie.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">kin\u014d, Masaki wa eiga wo mimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u304d\u306e\u3046\u3001\u307e\u3055\u304d \u306f \u3048\u3044\u304c \u3092 \u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u6628\u65e5<rt>\u304d\u306e\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3001\u307e\u3055\u304d\u306f<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/16-masaki-kino-eiga-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Masaki wa kin\u014d, eiga wo mimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2551\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/16-masaki-kino-eiga-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/16-masaki-kino-eiga-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/16-masaki-kino-eiga-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/16-masaki-kino-eiga-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/16-masaki-kino-eiga-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Yesterday, Masaki watched a movie.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Yesterday, Masaki watched a movie.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Masaki wa kin\u014d, eiga wo mimashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u307e\u3055\u304d \u306f \u304d\u306e\u3046\u3001 \u3048\u3044\u304c \u3092 \u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\">\u307e\u3055\u304d\u306f<ruby>\u6628\u65e5<rt>\u304d\u306e\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3001<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>As shown, the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kin\u014d&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304d\u306e\u3046\u300d<\/span> can appear either before the topic or in the &#8220;Other Information&#8221; section, just like <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kay\u014dbi ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u706b\u66dc\u65e5<rt>\u304b\u3088\u3046\u3073<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b\u300d<\/span>. (And yes, it can also come after <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;eiga wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u300d<\/span>).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Read also:<\/strong> <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/time-expressions\/\">Japanese Expressions of Time (and when to use the particle &#8220;ni&#8221;)<\/a><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"key-takeaways\">Key Takeaways<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The particle &#8220;ni&#8221; has three main uses. Here are the main points to remember for each:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong><em>To mark the destination of an action involving movement<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>&#8220;Destination + <span class=\"ilRom\">ni<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u306b<\/span>&#8221; usually appears somewhere between the &#8220;Topic + <span class=\"ilRom\">wa<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u306f<\/span>&#8221; and the verb<\/li><li>Has a few unexpected applications, such as with the verbs <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;norimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u4e57<rt>\u306e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> (ride) and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;suwarimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5ea7<rt>\u3059\u308f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> (sit)<\/li><li>Subtly different to particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;he&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3078\u300d<\/span>, which generally marks the direction rather than the destination, though these are often interchangeable<\/li><li>Meaning flips to mark the origin when used with verbs of a passive nature (such as <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> or the passive form of active verbs)<\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p><strong><em>To mark the location where something exists<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>&#8220;Location of existence + <span class=\"ilRom\">ni<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u306b<\/span>&#8221; usually appears somewhere between the &#8220;Topic + <span class=\"ilRom\">wa<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u306f<\/span>&#8221; and the verb<\/li><li>Only used for verbs describing &#8220;existence&#8221;, particularly <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;arimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;imasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/li><li>For the location where an action takes place, use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;de&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u300d<\/span> instead<\/li><li>Often used when saying the equivalent of, &#8220;there is&#8230;&#8221;<\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p><strong><em>To mark the time when an action takes place<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>&#8220;Timing + <span class=\"ilRom\">ni<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u306b<\/span>&#8221; can appear basically anywhere before the verb, including before the Topic<\/li><li>Particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is not required for time expressions describing a point in time relative to &#8220;now&#8221; (eg. today, yesterday, next year, etc.)<\/li><\/ul>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The particle &#8220;ni&#8221;\u300c\u306b\u300d is extremely common, and a big reason for that is because it has so many applications. In this article we\u2019re going to look at the three most important uses of the particle &#8220;ni&#8221;\u300c\u306b\u300d: To mark the destination of an action involving movement To mark the location where something exists To mark the [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":4,"featured_media":2613,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[4,5],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-2348","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-grammar","category-structure","post-wrapper","thrv_wrapper"],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v25.9 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>How to use the particle NI for destinations, locations and time - 80\/20 Japanese<\/title>\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet:-1, max-image-preview:large, max-video-preview:-1\" \/>\n<link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-ni\/\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:locale\" content=\"en_US\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"How to use the particle NI for destinations, locations and time - 80\/20 Japanese\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"The particle &#8220;ni&#8221;\u300c\u306b\u300d is extremely common, and a big reason for that is because it has so many applications. In this article we\u2019re going to look at the three most important uses of the particle &#8220;ni&#8221;\u300c\u306b\u300d: To mark the 